  "prompt": "What is nerve cell?",
  "response": "A nerve cell, also known as a neuron, is a specialized cell that transmits information throughout the nervous system. Neurons are essential for receiving, processing, and sending signals in the form of electrical impulses to and from different parts of the body. They communicate with each other and with other types of cells, such as muscle cells and gland cells, through synapses, which are junctions where neurotransmitters are released.\n\nKey features of nerve cells include:\n\n1. **Cell Structure**: Neurons typically consist of three main parts:\n   - **Cell Body (Soma)**: Contains the nucleus and cell organelles. It integrates signals received from other neurons.\n   - **Dendrites**: These are tree-like extensions that receive messages from other neurons. They increase the surface area for receiving signals.\n   - **Axon**: A long, slender projection that transmits electrical impulses away from the cell body to other neurons, muscles, or glands. The axon may be myelinated, meaning it is covered with a fatty sheath (myelin) that speeds up signal transmission.\n\n2. **Types of Neurons**: Neurons can be classified into different types based on their function:\n   - **Sensory Neurons**: Relay information from sensory receptors (like those for sight, sound, and touch) to the central nervous system (CNS).\n   - **Motor Neurons**: Carry signals from the CNS to muscle cells, triggering movement.\n   - **Interneurons**: Connect neurons within the CNS and are involved in processing information.\n\n3. **Function**: Neurons are responsible for various functions, including:\n   - Propagation of action potentials (electrical signals).\n   - Transmission of signals across synapses through neurotransmitters.\n   - Integration and processing of information in the brain and spinal cord.\n\nOverall, nerve cells play a crucial role in controlling bodily functions and behaviors, making them fundamental to the operation of the nervous system.",
